post_text:
The 14th annual Cat Tracks 5K Trail Run/Walk is going virtual! You will have between Saturday, August 29, 2020, and Sunday, September 6, 2020, to complete your race.

Due to the recommendations from the CDC and the State of Michigan, we are changing Cat Tracks 5K Trail Run/Walk into a virtual race. With a virtual race, you can run the distance anywhere, for example in your neighborhood, on a treadmill, at a nearby park, or on our original course!

Proceeds from this race will support youth initiative at Brandywine Community Schools.

Where: Anywhere!
When: Saturday, August 29-Sunday, September 6

Learn more at https://runsignup.com/Race/MI/Niles/CatTracks5k

As we continue our planning for the upcoming school year, we are asking for feedback on the remote learning that took place during the COVID-19 closure from April 20 - June 9, 2020 and for your plans for the upcoming school year. We will use this information to strengthen our remote learning curriculum IF the district is required to do so again. There are 2 surveys to complete: one for families and one for students. Please complete the appropriate surveys and submit by Friday, July 17th.

Specific questions about the surveys should be directed to either the building principals or Ms. Weimer, the superintendent.

Thank you so much for taking the time to assist the district with our ongoing planning.

Student Survey: https://forms.gle/4mDehKA44t1YXghk6

Parent/Guardian Survey: https://forms.gle/gkBXfwdtEfLgAK9L9

post_text:
Dear Seniors and Parents:

As you know, 3 dates have been set aside for possible in person graduation ceremonies. Unfortunately, we now know that we cannot hold a ceremony on June 13th. However, July 11th and August 8th still remain as possible dates, and we will continue to monitor the Governor's Executive Orders and guidelines from health organizations to determine when we are able to safely hold an in person ceremony. Please note that alternative graduation ideas may also be considered.

Caps and Gowns/Senior Products: The school does not have the products at this time. Additional information will be available next week regarding safe distribution of the products.

Mr. Weckel

In an effort to streamline communication regarding the district's shift to remote learning, the majority of information will be posted on the district's website under the heading Continuity of Learning Plan. Teachers may also be directly communicating with students/parents with specific information. We are in the process of posting the different documents, so your patience is appreciated as we work to get that completed.

As a reminder, implementation of our remote learning plan begins on Monday, April 20th.

If you cannot find the appropriate information on the district's website (https://www.brandywinebobcats.org/), please contact your child's teacher or their principal. Thank you so much for your continued support and cooperation.

post_text:
With the updated shutdown of face to face contact for the remainder of the schoo; year, we feel it is important that we again offer chromebooks to those families who don’t have one to use. Beginning next Monday, April 20th we will be implementing continuous online learning for the remainder of the year and it will be necessary to have some device to connect online. For that reason we will be doing a drive up chromebook pickup for students in grades 7-12 who still don’t have access to a device. This pickup will take place on Thursday April 16th from 10 a.m. until 2 p.m. at the High School. If these times do not work for you, please contact our helpdesk at help@brandywinebobcats.org or call 269-683-4800 extension 3224.

Merritt and Brandywine Elementary students should contact their teachers if they need a device

Last night Governor Gretchen Whitmer ordered all K - 12 schools closed from March 16th - April 5th. All Brandywine schools are open today. More district specific information is forthcoming. Thank you for your continued cooperation as we navigate through this new territory.

Governor Gretchen Whitmer
March 12 at 11:22 PM ·

Tonight, I announced that in order to slow the spread of COVID-19 in Michigan, I am ordering the closure of all K-12 school buildings, public, private, and boarding, to students starting Monday, March 16 until Sunday, April 5. School buildings are scheduled to reopen on Monday, April 6.

I am working with partners across state government to ensure educators, parents, and students have the support they need, and to ensure our children who rely on school for meals have access to food.

I know this will be a tough time, but we’re doing this to keep the most people we can safe. I urge everyone to make smart choices during this time and to do everything they can to protect themselves and their families.

Information around this outbreak is changing rapidly. The latest information is available at Michigan.gov/Coronavirus and CDC.gov/Coronavirus

post_text:
Safety of our students is of utmost concern at Brandywine Community Schools, so we are keeping you informed of what is happening currently at Brandywine.

The Brandywine district was notified this afternoon of a situation that was occurring in close proximity to our schools. As a precaution, all schools went in to a perimeter lockdown. After updated information from the Berrien County Sheriff's office, MS/HS and Brandywine Elementary are no longer in a lock down, and dismissal will take place as usual. Parents may pick up students there if they choose.

However, at the order of the Berrien County Sherriff's Office, Merrritt Elementary is remaining in a perimeter lock down and we will not be allowing anyone in or out of Merritt until further notice.

Everyone is safe, and this has been a precautionary measure for an off campus incident. Thank you for your cooperation.

post_text:
Information Sessions for Possible School Board Members

On November 6, 2018, there will be an election for Brandywine school board members, and there are 4 open positions. If you have ever considered running for the school board, but did not know what all was involved, now is the time to get your questions answered.

Current Board members will be available to answer questions from 6:00 – 6:30 p.m. on June 11th, June 25th and July 9th at Brandywine Innovation Academy, which is located at 1830 S. 3rd Street. There will be a School Board meeting following each of these informational sessions, and this would be a perfect opportunity to see the Board in action.

This is an excellent way to have meaningful involvement in your community and school district. Please consider attending an informational session on June 11th, 25th or July 9th.

In the district’s efforts to continue to build on safety in our community, on Wednesday, March 28 at 6 p.m., we invite you to Niles High School for Partners in Safety: A Community Town Hall.

During this forum, Niles Community Schools, Brandywine Community Schools, Buchanan Community Schools, and the Niles Police Department invite all members of the community to participate in a discussion about safety. We’ll discuss crisis preparedness efforts underway at area schools and across the community, and talk openly about what we can do collectively to ensure our children’s safety during these trying times.

post_text:
Dear Brandywine Community,
Mrs. Martha Shreve spent her entire career teaching Kindergarten at Brandywine. After her retirement, she went to work volunteering for over 15 years at Brandywine Elementary School. Unfortunately, Mrs. Shreve is no longer able to help out physically, but the Brandywine community remains in her heart and soul.
If you would like to reach out to her to thank her for helping you, or a child, or even as a staff member, please send her a card. We would like to shower her with our thanks and gratitude. Cards can be sent to Mrs. Shreve in care of Merritt Elementary School, 1620 LaSalle Avenue, Niles, Michigan 49120, and will be delivered to her.
On behalf of our colleague, thank you!
text:
Dear Brandywine Community,

If you would like to reach out to her to thank her for helping you, or a child, or even as a staff member, please send her a card. We would like to shower her with our thanks and gratitude. Cards can be sent to Mrs. Shreve in care of Merritt Elementary School, 1620 LaSalle Avenue, Niles, Michigan 49120, and will be delivered to her.
On behalf of our colleague, thank you!

post_text:
BRANDYWINE TO DISCUSS PROJECTS

At the Board of Education meeting on Monday, November 14, the Board will hear about plans for these projects:
- More dollars available for projects since our sinking fund was passed.
- Taking care of identified roofing needs.
- Curriculum/instruction personnel needs.
- Improving fine arts performance facilities.
- Entrance and exit driveway improvements at Middle/Senior High School.
- Possible new multi-purpose building for students and community.
- Possible new tennis courts.
- Possible re-location of the baseball field.

Our meeting will be at the Brandywine Innovation Academy, 1830 South third (formerly Bell School). We start at 7:00 PM and
the public is invited.

post_text:
We have sad news to share. Former Brandywine teacher and principal Melba Ross passed away last week-end. She was 80 years old. Many Bobcats remember Mrs. Ross, a small but strong educator who had lots of energy every single day.

Here are the arrangements for Melba ross: Memorial and prayer services will be Friday, July 15 at 7:00 PM at Handmaids of the Most Holy Trinity Monastery, 23089 Adams Rd., South Bend.
Funeral mass is at St. Joseph Catholic Church, 226 N. Hill, South Bend, Saturday at 10:30.

Here's a link to the obituary:

http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/southbendtribune/obituary.aspx?n=melba-ann-ross&pid=180636541&fhid=8823
